"Bomber poured into a tulip, another brew from the initial wave of Stone offerings to arrive in Alberta. I enjoy reading the wordy tangential musings on these labels. This brew is on the light side color wise, a bronze amber with a small amount of frothy beige foam in top. Does leave a nice thick lacing on the glass. Aroma is rich and sweet, Christmas pudding-like with some toasted grains, dark fruits, brown sugar, and cinnamon/nutmeg/ginger all nicely melded together. Dangerously smooth and drinkable, comes across as light-medium bodied (its easy to forget that even the biggest Trappist/abbey ales are still supposed to err on the side of drinkable, to hear the monks talk). Gentle carbonation. Malts evoke honeyed breakfast cereal and a little chocolate pudding, molasses, and a puff of dark roast wheat. Getting a decent dose of orchard and tropical fruit on the nose and palate, mango (!), orange, and poached pears. Cinnamon, nutmeg, and white pepper spice round out the flavor profile. Rich sweet taste but does not become cloying, with more emphasis on malts and fruity hops than classic Belgian spicy phenols. Certainly a unique take on the style, with west coast hop flourishes and a rounded sweetness that can be less apparent in the true Belgian examples. Bold like most Stone beers yet with a pleasing subtle complexity."
""
""
""
"An interesting breakdown of what a Quadruple-style ale can and could be, beyond the more delineated BSDA guidelines - pick yer grains, and go to town, son!  Way more drinkable than I sadly prepared myself for (sorry, Stone), but still all new-world in its complexity, which is a miser's trade-off, to be sure.  Whatever, I'm enjoying making my way through this, and for that, I am one content lab rat."
