"Poured into a Gavroche tulip. Pours a dark chestnut amber with a fine, half-finger khaki head with good retention and lacing. Aroma of mild caramel malt, apple family fruit, Belgian yeast, mild dark stone fruit; sweet. Flavor starts with dark dried fruit, coriander, rye sourness, brown sugar. Transitions to a slightly overspiced odd grain flavor, probably the triticale that kind of reminded me of the lightly vegetal flavor in gluten free beers, finishes with an interesting but somewhat unbalanced spiciness from the rye and Belgian spices. Medium, nearly syrupy body with light carbonation. An interesting experiment and a passable quad style ale, but not comparable to the traditional flavors. Works as an odd, spicy, dark fruit Belgian style ale. This grew on me as I drank it and started appreciating the flavors for the non-traditional element they represented. I wouldn't get this again if in the mood for a quad, but definitely wouldn't mind tasting it again. Pleasant way to find out what triticale would taste like in a beer. They need a bit of quality control on the process, I got a small tuft of tribble fur in my glass."
