"a really poor beer from stone, and i know they arent the kings of the belgians or anything, and i know triticale is a tough grain, uncommon in brewing, and an adventure to begin with, but i feel like they could have done a lot more to showcase it, this base beer is weak street. listed only flaked triticale and pilsener malt on the label, the watery brown color must surely come from the addition of the dark sugar. its got a decent tan head on it, and some rising bubbles, but the nose is odd. tons of leftover sugar, but still harshly bitter, i imagine thats the triticale coming through pungently. generic belgian ale yeast does nothing for it. the flavor is just appalling, i mean, really bad, and it takes a lot for me to say that about a beer. its course and bitter, but the candy sugar doesnt belong here, its sweet, not fully fermented out, and instead of balancing the intensity of the cool new grain, it simply distracts form it with a fake maple syrup corn sugar kind of thing. its gross really. nothing about this is belgian quad at all, and the yeast is not strong enough to clean up the sugar. the body is extremely watery too, even with good carbonation its just way too light for both the flavors and the style. harsh and long lasting bitter finish from the grain, no hops here at all, really unpleasant. i am not sold on triticale as a brewing grain, but this beer from stone was a poor attempt in my opinion. it was weighed down by all that added sugar and alcohol, and really misses the mark. i suspect a pale saison may work better with this grain, even an english type pale ale would be worth trying, but this is confounded in so many ways. definitely a drain pour."
